<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,152,335]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,333,270,296]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Etymology</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[371,633,271,296]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="thompsonii">
<emphasis box="[371,633,271,296]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Stauroneis thompsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is named for David Thompson (1770–1857), an early 19 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1320,1332,267,281]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">th</superScript>
Century 
<collectingRegion box="[151,255,309,335]" country="United States of America" name="Montana" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Montana</collectingRegion>
explorer and cartographer (
<bibRefCitation author="Jenish" box="[580,726,309,335]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" refId="ref3720" refString="Jenish, D'Arcy (2003) Epic wanderer: David Thompson and the mapping of the Canadian West. Doubleday Canada, Toronto." type="book" year="2003">Jenish 2003</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5065938" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5065938" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5065938/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" startId="4.[151,257,1904,1925]" targetBox="[194,1365,377,1800]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1904,2030]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,320,1904,1925]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">FIGURES 9–24:</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[326,713,1905,1926]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[326,548,1905,1926]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="sacajaweae">Stauroneis sacajaweae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[558,708,1905,1926]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="spauldingiae">S. spauldingiae</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[760,891,1905,1926]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="thompsonii">
<emphasis box="[760,891,1905,1926]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">S. thompsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Figs 9–15: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[1012,1231,1905,1926]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="sacajaweae">
<emphasis box="[1012,1231,1905,1926]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Stauroneis sacajaweae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Figs 9, 11–15: Type locality. Fig. 10: Haystack Seep, Going-To-The-Sun Road, Glacier National Park, Montana. Figs 16–21: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[1153,1383,1938,1959]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="spauldingiae">
<emphasis box="[1153,1383,1938,1959]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Stauroneis spauldingiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Figs 16–18, 20, 21: Copper Lake, Shoshone County, Idaho (type locality). Fig. 19: Lily Lake, Lemhi County, Idaho. Figs 22–24: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="thompsonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Stauroneis thompsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the type locality.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,294]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,374,151,177]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Observations:</emphasis>
— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bahls" authorityYear="2012" box="[403,667,152,177]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="thompsonii">
<emphasis box="[403,667,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Stauroneis thompsonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bahls, L." box="[883,1086,152,178]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="ref3484" refString="Bahls, L. (2010) Stauroneis in the Northern Rockies - 50 species of Stauroneis sensu stricto from western Montana, northern Idaho, northeastern Washington and southwestern Alberta, including 16 species described as new. Vol. 4 In: Bahls, L. (Ed.), Northwest Diatoms, Montana Diatom Collection, Helena, 179 pp." type="book" year="2010">Bahls (2010: 61)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName authority="Van de Vijver &amp; Lange-Bertalot (2004: 27)" authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Lange-Bertalot" authorityPageNumber="27" authorityYear="2004" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="catharinae">
<emphasis box="[1132,1154,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">S.</emphasis>
aff. 
<emphasis box="[1214,1341,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">catharinae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Van de Vijver, B. &amp; Beyens, L. &amp; Lange-Bertalot, H." pageId="5" pageNumber="6" refId="ref4449" refString="Van de Vijver, B., Beyens, L. &amp; Lange-Bertalot, H. (2004) The Genus Stauroneis in the Arctic and (Sub-) Antarctic Regions. Bibliotheca Diatomologica, Band 51. J. Cramer, Berlin, 317 pp." type="book" year="2004">Van de Vijver &amp; Lange-Bertalot (2004: 27)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. However, it has significantly wider valves and lower stria and areola densities than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Lange-Bertalot" authorityYear="2004" box="[328,491,229,254]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Stauroneidaceae" genus="Stauroneis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="catharinae">
<emphasis box="[328,491,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">S. catharinae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[832,884,229,255]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">type</typeStatus>
locality, a small lake in the Galton Range in northwest 
<collectingRegion box="[274,378,268,294]" country="United States of America" name="Montana" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Montana</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[394,482,268,294]" captionStart="FIGURE 25" captionStartId="5.[151,245,1968,1989]" captionTargetBox="[258,1329,471,1946]" captionTargetId="figure-108@5.[258,1329,335,1946]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 25: Wolverine Lakes in the Galton Range, northwest Montana. Upper Wolverine Lake (foreground) is the type locality of Stauroneis thompsonii and typical of habitats for Stauroneis species in the northern Rocky Mountains. Photo by the author." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5065940" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5065940/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
